      <h2 class="govuk-heading-l">Making a Victim Personal Statement</h2>
      <p class="govuk-body-l">This guidance is for when you experience a crime in England and Wales.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">You have the right to make a Victim Personal Statement, which tells the court how a crime has affected you. It is included when the judge or magistrates are deciding on the sentence for a defendant.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">This is different to your witness statement. It is for you to say how the crime has affected you, whether physically, emotionally, financially or in any other way.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">It can also be called a VPS or a ‘Victim Impact Statement’.</p>

      <h3 class="govuk-heading-m">When you give the statement</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body">You can choose to give your Victim Personal Statement to the police when you report the crime, or up until the case goes to court.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">You can also make an updated statement until the case goes to court. It’s important to remember that as a Victim Personal Statement is a legal document, even if you make a new one later on, any previous ones you have made are kept on record.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">You can also ask to read your Victim Personal Statement out in court if you want to.</p>

      <h3 class="govuk-heading-m">How the statement can help your case</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body">Your Victim Personal Statement helps the court, police, and prosecutors understand the emotional, physical, and financial effects the crime has had on you and your life.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">If a defendant is found guilty, the court will take your Victim Personal Statement into account, along with all the other evidence, when deciding on an appropriate sentence.</p>

      <h3 class="govuk-heading-m">How to write a Victim Personal Statement</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body">You can consider writing in your own words about how the crime has affected different parts of your life, such as your:</p>
      <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
        <li>mental health</li>
        <li>physical health</li>
        <li>money</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="govuk-body">For example, you might write about:</p>
      <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
        <li>an injury and its effects on your life</li>
        <li>medical treatment or therapy you have had</li>
        <li>feeling vulnerable, intimidated or unsafe</li>
        <li>effects on your family</li>
        <li>how your quality of life has changed on a day-to-day basis</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="govuk-body">You can get more advice and support to help you write your statement from the police.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">A victim of crime must write their Victim Personal Statement themself. The law allows someone else to write it when the victim:</p>
      <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
        <li>is not able because of illness, injury, or mental health – a representative such as a close family member can write it</li>
        <li>is aged under 18 – their parent or carer can write it, if appropriate</li>
        <li>has died – a family member can write it</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="govuk-body">Find out more about making a <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/victim-personal-statement" class="govuk-link" target="_blank">Victim Personal Statement (opens in new tab)</a>.</p>
